# Barrel Export Convention

Each module has **exactly one `index.ts`** at its root (e.g. `src/auth2/index.ts`). No `index.ts` files are allowed inside subdirectories.

## Rules

- **One `index.ts` per module root** — this is the only public entry point for library consumers.
- **No internal barrel files** — subdirectories (`aggregates/`, `commands/`, `dtos/`, `errors/`, etc.) must NOT contain `index.ts`.
- **Intra-module imports** must use direct file paths, never a directory path that resolves to an `index.ts`.
- **Implementation files** must have descriptive names (e.g. `auth2.errors.ts`, `auth2-response.dtos.ts`) — never `index.ts`.
- The module `index.ts` must only export symbols that **library consumers** are allowed to use — never expose domain aggregates, infrastructure, or application handlers.

## Examples

```ts
// ❌ BAD — importing via a directory barrel
import { ApiKeyNotFoundError } from '../../../domain/errors';
import { ApiKeyResponseDto } from '../../dtos/response';

// ✅ GOOD — importing directly from the concrete file
import { ApiKeyNotFoundError } from '../../../domain/errors/auth2.errors';
import { ApiKeyResponseDto } from '../../dtos/response/auth2-response.dtos';
```

```ts
// ❌ BAD — internal index.ts barrel in a subdirectory
// src/auth2/domain/errors/index.ts  ← must not exist
// src/auth2/application/commands/generate-api-key/index.ts  ← must not exist

// ✅ GOOD — single module-level barrel only
// src/auth2/index.ts  ← the only index.ts in the module
```

The module-level `index.ts` exports named symbols explicitly — never `export *` from internal directories:

```ts
// ❌ BAD — wildcard re-export hides what is actually public
export * from './presentation/decorators';

// ✅ GOOD — explicit named exports make the public API obvious
export { CurrentUser } from './presentation/decorators/current-user.decorator';
export { RequirePermissions } from './presentation/decorators/require-permissions.decorator';
```
